00:01:03.080 --> 00:01:06.870
And today, I'm delighted
to tip both my dean's hat

00:01:06.870 --> 00:01:10.060
and my professorial
hat to Professor Carol

00:01:10.060 --> 00:01:13.030
Oja, my colleague
in American studies

00:01:13.030 --> 00:01:16.170
and a fellow at the Radcliffe
Institute this year.

00:01:16.170 --> 00:01:18.630
And Carol will deliver
this afternoon's lecture,

00:01:18.630 --> 00:01:19.940
as you know.

00:01:19.940 --> 00:01:23.250
I realize that today may
be the first introduction

00:01:23.250 --> 00:01:25.960
to the Radcliffe
Institute for many of you.

00:01:25.960 --> 00:01:27.600
So I'd like to
just take a moment

00:01:27.600 --> 00:01:33.010
to explain a bit more about
who we are and what we do.

00:01:33.010 --> 00:01:36.010
As Harvard's Institute
for Advanced Study,

00:01:36.010 --> 00:01:38.360
Radcliffe is one
of the 13 schools

00:01:38.360 --> 00:01:41.070
that make up Harvard University.

00:01:41.070 --> 00:01:45.000
As I mentioned a moment ago,
we carry out a dual mission.

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:48.810
First, we cultivate a uniquely
interdisciplinary intellectual

00:01:48.810 --> 00:01:51.940
community, in which faculty
and students from Harvard

00:01:51.940 --> 00:01:55.180
and leading thinkers
from around the world all

00:01:55.180 --> 00:01:58.830
engage in scholarship,
scientific investigation,

00:01:58.830 --> 00:02:02.570
and the creative arts
across many academic fields.

00:02:02.570 --> 00:02:05.550
And second, we are
dedicated to sharing

00:02:05.550 --> 00:02:07.740
cutting edge work
with the public

00:02:07.740 --> 00:02:10.919
by hosting free events
like today's lecture,

00:02:10.919 --> 00:02:14.590
and then posting videos of
our lectures and conferences

00:02:14.590 --> 00:02:17.230
on our Radcliffe website.

00:02:17.230 --> 00:02:21.630
We pursue our dual mission
through three core programs.

00:02:21.630 --> 00:02:24.480
The first of our core programs
is our Radcliffe fellowship

00:02:24.480 --> 00:02:25.140
program.

00:02:25.140 --> 00:02:29.120
Every year, we bring 50
scholars, scientists,

00:02:29.120 --> 00:02:32.960
and artists to campus
as Fellows to work

00:02:32.960 --> 00:02:35.260
at the forefront
of their fields and

00:02:35.260 --> 00:02:37.920
across disciplinary boundaries.

00:02:37.920 --> 00:02:41.790
Today's speaker, Carol Oja is
this year's Frieda L. Miller

00:02:41.790 --> 00:02:45.760
Fellow, and I'm very pleased to
have Frieda Miller's son, Myron

00:02:45.760 --> 00:02:48.110
Miller, here with us today.

00:02:48.110 --> 00:02:51.470
The Frieda Miller Fellowship
was established in Frieda's name

00:02:51.470 --> 00:02:54.330
by Myron's late
father, Herman Miller,

00:02:54.330 --> 00:02:57.896
to honor Frieda's passionate
belief in higher education.

00:02:57.896 --> 00:03:01.340
And I have to say that I
have a special affection

00:03:01.340 --> 00:03:03.690
for the Miller
Fellowship, for the Miller

00:03:03.690 --> 00:03:06.970
family and the fellowship,
because the Frieda L. Miller

00:03:06.970 --> 00:03:10.520
gift was, in fact, the gift
that funded my Radcliffe

00:03:10.520 --> 00:03:15.010
Fellowship when I was a
Radcliffe Fellow in 2001 too.

00:03:15.010 --> 00:03:18.010
In addition to Carol,
this year's Fellows

00:03:18.010 --> 00:03:21.970
include leading thinkers from
six different continents.

00:03:21.970 --> 00:03:24.350
They are studying
everything from the origins

00:03:24.350 --> 00:03:28.140
of the universe, to marvels
in late medieval literature,

00:03:28.140 --> 00:03:30.590
to human rights
in Latin America.

00:03:30.590 --> 00:03:32.340
And this year's
artists are creating

00:03:32.340 --> 00:03:36.910
everything from sculptures,
to poems, to operas.

00:03:36.910 --> 00:03:39.870
Our second major program
is the Schlesinger Library,

00:03:39.870 --> 00:03:42.650
which is the foremost
library dedicated

00:03:42.650 --> 00:03:46.810
to the history of women and
gender in the United States.

00:03:46.810 --> 00:03:50.260
Recently, the library has
made a substantial commitment

00:03:50.260 --> 00:03:53.120
to telling the fullest,
most inclusive story

00:03:53.120 --> 00:03:55.810
of the American
past by taking steps

00:03:55.810 --> 00:03:59.930
to diversify our holdings to
include collections from women

00:03:59.930 --> 00:04:04.060
and organizations across every
racial class, geographical,

00:04:04.060 --> 00:04:06.070
and political divide.

00:04:06.070 --> 00:04:08.060
To that end, the
Schlesinger Library

00:04:08.060 --> 00:04:10.260
